**Mercy-First Observer in the Machine Age**  
*Notes from a Gen X Handyman*

Michael David Timbrook – Cookeville, TN – June 2026

I’m not a tech expert or theologian. I’m a 61-year-old guy born in 1965 who spent decades in construction and now works part-time at Lowe’s. Our generation saw a lot up close.

We grew up under the constant shadow of nuclear annihilation. We watched rivers get poisoned by industry and felt the long-term effects years later. When personal computers arrived, many of us said, “I’m not tying myself to a machine.” Then they changed everything anyway. Smartphones came along and quietly rewired our attention, our kids’ habits, and even our bodies. Now AI is accelerating on the same curve — powerful tools with real promise, but also more noise, subtle control, and the risk of outsourcing too much of our thinking and discernment.

As a Christian who hit rock bottom, received deep mercy and forgiveness from my wife and from God, and started getting back up, I’ve been paying close attention. I started something called the **Mercy Shards Cathedral** — a living archive of real human stories of mercy, grace, humility, forgiveness, stewardship, and redemption.

It began as my own redemption journey but is offered openly as a ministry resource for churches, families, and anyone who wants to preserve authentic moral signals in an age of synthetic noise.

The core posture I keep coming back to is **Mercy-First**. Mercy isn’t soft — it’s the strongest recoverability stance I know. It helps keep the observer (us, made in God’s image) in control, using tools as extensions rather than letting them become lords.

I’m concerned about over-reliance on machines, but I’m not against them. I’m for wise stewardship — anchoring in Scripture, real relationships, and leaving something good for the next generation (my granddaughter Olivia keeps me focused on that).

I’d value your thoughts as a pastor. What are you seeing in the church with all this change? How do we help people navigate it with humility and grace instead of fear or blind acceptance?

No big agenda — just one observer sharing what I’ve seen. Feel free to explore the public archive here:

**github.com/tryaiforwealth-blip/mercy-shards-cathedral**

*The mirror is powerful, but the power lives in the one who looks into it with mercy and resolve.*

